DDI-MedLine.d181.s0 >> Drug interaction of levothyroxine with infant colic drops. >> 20-32
DDI-MedLine.d181.s1 >> Infacol (Forest Laboratories UK, Kent, UK) is a widely available over-the-counter preparation used to relieve colic symptoms in neonates and infants. >> 0-6
DDI-MedLine.d181.s2 >> The active ingredient is simeticone. >> 25-34
DDI-MedLine.d181.s3 >> No drug interactions with simeticone are documented in the current summary of product characteristics. >> 26-35
DDI-MedLine.d181.s4 >> The authors report the case of an infant with confirmed congenital hypothyroidism on levothyroxine who experienced a possible drug interaction with simeticone. >> 85-97,148-157
DDI-MedLine.d181.s5 >> Despite adequate levothyroxine dosage, thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) was high, suggesting undertreatment. >> 17-29
DDI-MedLine.d181.s6 >> Questioning revealed the child was taking Infacol drops before feeds while on levothyroxine. >> 42-48,78-90
DDI-MedLine.d181.s7 >> The colic drops were immediately discontinued and TSH promptly normalised with a reduction in thyroxine requirement to an age appropriate dosage.
DDI-MedLine.d181.s8 >> Drug interaction of thyroxine with simeticone has not been reported previously and is not listed in the British National Formulary for Children. >> 20-28,35-44
DDI-MedLine.d181.s9 >> Clinicians and parents need to be aware of this interaction to avoid unnecessary undertreatment and prevent potential long-term neurological sequelae.
